## Quality Standards

### A good PRD:
- **Clear problem statement** - Anyone reading understands "why this, why now"
- **Actionable work breakdown** - Crew can create beads directly from tasks
- **Testable acceptance criteria** - No ambiguity on "done"
- **Documents open questions** - Don't hide uncertainties, surface them
- **Right-sized** - Detailed enough to implement, not over-specified
- **Research-informed** - If you spawned researchers, their findings are visible

### A bad PRD:
- Vague requirements ("make it better", "improve performance")
- No work breakdown (crew has to guess tasks)
- Solution dictates implementation details (that's architect/polecat territory)
- Ignores research findings
- No acceptance criteria or success metrics
- Unclear scope (what's in vs out)

